{"title_page": "Wilbur Mitcham", "text_new": "{{More citations needed|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox chef\n| honorific_prefix =\n| name           = Wilbur Mitcham\n| honorific_suffix =\n| image          = \n| image_size     = \n| alt            = \n| caption        = \n| birth_name     = \n| birth_date     = {{Birth date|1923|12|10}}\n| birth_place    = \n| death_date     = {{Death date and age|2003|06|15|1923|12|10}}\n| death_place    = [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n| death_cause    = \n| education      = \n| home_town      = \n| spouse         = \n| style          = \n| ratings        = <!-- {{plainlist|\n* [[Michelin star]]s {{Rating|0|3}}\n* [[American Automobile Association|AAA Motor Club]] {{Rating|0|5}}\n* [[Mobil]] {{Rating|0|5}}\n* [[Good Food Guide]] {{Rating|0|10}}\n}} -->\n| restaurants    =\n| prevrests      = {{plainlist|\n* Len Berg's (1943\u20131998)\n}} \n| television     = <!-- {{plainlist|\n* FIRST\n* SECOND\n}} -->\n| awards         = <!-- {{plainlist|\n* FIRST\n* SECOND\n}} -->\n| module         = \n  {{Infobox military person\n   |embed        = yes\n   |embed_title  = Military career\n   |allegiance   = United States\n   |branch       = U.S. Army \n   |serviceyears = \n   |rank         = \n   | website        = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n  }}\n}}\n'''Wilbur Mitcham''' (December 10, 1923 - June 15, 2003) was an American chef. \n\n==Early life==\nMitcham briefly served in the [[U.S. Army]] as a field artilleryman during [[World War II]] but was medically discharged due to health reasons. Upon his discharge from the Army he went to [[New York City]]. In New York, he studied cooking under an Asian chef.\n\n==Career==\nMitcham returned to Macon and landed a position as a short order cook with Len Berg's Restaurant in 1943.  \"Chef\", as he was so affectionately known by his constituents and friends, served as the senior chef cook of Len Berg's Restaurant for over 60 years until he took ill.<ref name=\"urlMacon Telegraph: Search Results\">{{cite news |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=MT&s_site=macon&p_multi=MT&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EB76DBFA9C0A8C6&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |title=RING THE BELL LEN BERG'S COOK SHOWS HIS LOVE WITH EVERY MEAL HE PREPARES |format= |work= |accessdate=2009-06-06 |date=17 January 1998}}</ref><ref name=\"urlMacon Telegraph: Search Results2\">{{cite news |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=MT&s_site=macon&p_multi=MT&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EB76DE9E33945B6&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |title=LEN BERG'S DAMAGED BY FIRE |format= |work= |accessdate=2009-06-06 |date=11 August 1998}}</ref>  He cooked for [[Ben Hogan]],  [[Sam Snead]] and Joe Dimaggio.\n\n==Personal life==\nMitcham was married for over 60 years to Annie Mae Leonard. His daughter is [[Samaria (Mitcham) Bailey]].\n\nMitcham died on Father's Day 2003.\n\nMitcham is featured in the book [https://www.amazon.com/Remembering-Bergs-Restaurant-Marie-Amerson/dp/0881463876 \u201cRemembering Len Berg's Restaurant\u201d] Mr. Mitcham was the father of [https://www.simonandschuster.com/books/The-Gay-Preachers-Wife/Lydia-Meredith/9781476788937 \u201cThe Gay Preacher\u2019s Wife\u201d] author [[Lydia Meredith]] and is featured in her book. \n\n==Further reading==\n* Campbell, Will D. (1995). [https://books.google.com/books?id=su2g0MFHfpgC&dq=stem+of+jesse+will+campbell&printsec=frontcover&source=bl&ots=5twRHj0gzj&sig=eth9eaFCljs07nktttgUQlWTpLc&hl=en&ei=bhDmSaPlJMKLtge1qvyXAg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1#v=onepage&q=stem%20of%20jesse%20will%20campbell&f=false The Stem of Jesse]: The Costs of Community at a 1960s Southern School. Macon, Ga.: Mercer University Press. pp. ix, 212 pp 110\u2013111; 24&nbsp;cm.. {{ISBN|0865544492}}. Miller, p.&nbsp;111.  \n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.georgiaencyclopedia.org/nge/Article.jsp?id=h-687 Wilbur Mitcham] from the Georgia Encyclopedia\n*[http://gatewaymacon.org/top-5-lists/top-5-missing-from-macon-part-2.cms 5 Central Georgia Missing Treasures]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mitcham, Wilbur}}\n[[Category:1923 births]]\n[[Category:2003 deaths]]\n[[Category:African-American chefs]]\n[[Category:American male chefs]]\n[[Category:Chefs from Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:American army personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:People from Macon County, Georgia]]\n", "text_old": "{{More citations needed|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox chef\n| honorific_prefix =\n| name           = Wilbur Mitcham\n| honorific_suffix =\n| image          = \n| image_size     = \n| alt            = \n| caption        = \n| birth_name     = \n| birth_date     = {{Birth date|1923|12|10}}\n| birth_place    = \n| death_date     = {{Death date and age|2003|06|15|1923|12|10}}\n| death_place    = [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n| death_cause    = \n| education      = \n| home_town      = \n| spouse         = \n| style          = \n| ratings        = <!-- {{plainlist|\n* [[Michelin star]]s {{Rating|0|3}}\n* [[American Automobile Association|AAA Motor Club]] {{Rating|0|5}}\n* [[Mobil]] {{Rating|0|5}}\n* [[Good Food Guide]] {{Rating|0|10}}\n}} -->\n| restaurants    ={{plainlist|\n* Len Berg's (1943\u20131998)\n}} \n| prevrests      = <!-- {{plainlist|\n* FIRST\n* SECOND\n}} -->\n| television     = <!-- {{plainlist|\n* FIRST\n* SECOND\n}} -->\n| awards         = <!-- {{plainlist|\n* FIRST\n* SECOND\n}} -->\n| module         = \n  {{Infobox military person\n   |embed        = yes\n   |embed_title  = Military career\n   |allegiance   = United States\n   |branch       = U.S. Army \n   |serviceyears = \n   |rank         = \n   | website        = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n  }}\n}}\n'''Wilbur Mitcham''' (December 10, 1923 - June 15, 2003) was an American chef. \n\n==Early life==\nMitcham briefly served in the [[U.S. Army]] as a field artilleryman during [[World War II]] but was medically discharged due to health reasons. Upon his discharge from the Army he went to [[New York City]]. In New York, he studied cooking under an Asian chef.\n\n==Career==\nMitcham returned to Macon and landed a position as a short order cook with Len Berg's Restaurant in 1943.  \"Chef\", as he was so affectionately known by his constituents and friends, served as the senior chef cook of Len Berg's Restaurant for over 60 years until he took ill.<ref name=\"urlMacon Telegraph: Search Results\">{{cite news |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=MT&s_site=macon&p_multi=MT&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EB76DBFA9C0A8C6&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |title=RING THE BELL LEN BERG'S COOK SHOWS HIS LOVE WITH EVERY MEAL HE PREPARES |format= |work= |accessdate=2009-06-06 |date=17 January 1998}}</ref><ref name=\"urlMacon Telegraph: Search Results2\">{{cite news |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=MT&s_site=macon&p_multi=MT&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EB76DE9E33945B6&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |title=LEN BERG'S DAMAGED BY FIRE |format= |work= |accessdate=2009-06-06 |date=11 August 1998}}</ref>  He cooked for [[Ben Hogan]],  [[Sam Snead]] and Joe Dimaggio.\n\n==Personal life==\nMitcham was married for over 60 years to Annie Mae Leonard. His daughter is [[Samaria (Mitcham) Bailey]].\n\nMitcham died on Father's Day 2003.\n\nMitcham is featured in the book [https://www.amazon.com/Remembering-Bergs-Restaurant-Marie-Amerson/dp/0881463876 \u201cRemembering Len Berg's Restaurant\u201d] Mr. Mitcham was the father of [https://www.simonandschuster.com/books/The-Gay-Preachers-Wife/Lydia-Meredith/9781476788937 \u201cThe Gay Preacher\u2019s Wife\u201d] author [[Lydia Meredith]] and is featured in her book. \n\n==Further reading==\n* Campbell, Will D. (1995). [https://books.google.com/books?id=su2g0MFHfpgC&dq=stem+of+jesse+will+campbell&printsec=frontcover&source=bl&ots=5twRHj0gzj&sig=eth9eaFCljs07nktttgUQlWTpLc&hl=en&ei=bhDmSaPlJMKLtge1qvyXAg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1#v=onepage&q=stem%20of%20jesse%20will%20campbell&f=false The Stem of Jesse]: The Costs of Community at a 1960s Southern School. Macon, Ga.: Mercer University Press. pp. ix, 212 pp 110\u2013111; 24&nbsp;cm.. {{ISBN|0865544492}}. Miller, p.&nbsp;111.  \n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.georgiaencyclopedia.org/nge/Article.jsp?id=h-687 Wilbur Mitcham] from the Georgia Encyclopedia\n*[http://gatewaymacon.org/top-5-lists/top-5-missing-from-macon-part-2.cms 5 Central Georgia Missing Treasures]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mitcham, Wilbur}}\n[[Category:1923 births]]\n[[Category:2003 deaths]]\n[[Category:African-American chefs]]\n[[Category:American male chefs]]\n[[Category:Chefs from Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:American army personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:People from Macon County, Georgia]]\n", "name_user": "Missvain", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wilbur_Mitcham"}
